--- !u!114 &4825946130230939283
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 4993465266696353118}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 69aa0ebf31678e4469bf777316b87aa7, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  AddContextToTheGameObject: "Left / Right keys or A/D will add force to the Dynamic
    Circle. The GameObject includes a 2D Circle Collider a Rigidbody2D, and a Sprite
    Renderer Component. \n\nRigidbodies control the physics properties related to
    movement in an object. \n\nColliders define the shape the object takes up and
    when it will interact with other objects. \n\nThere are two parallel physics
    systems in Unity. They are very similar except one is for 3D and one is for 2D.
    Note that they will NOT interact with each other, so make sure all your colliders
    and rigidbodies are the 2D variety (will have 2d in the name). \n\nRigidbody
    types: Rigidbody is a 3D Rigidbody used for 3D collisions, and Rigidbody2D is
    used for 2D movement. \nSimilarly with colliders, A collider that doesn't have
    2d means it is for 3D (Sphere, Cube etc) while a collider that has 2d in the
    name is for the 2d physics system (Circle2d, Box2d, etc. ) \n\n"
